<br>
The items you have recieved have blinded you to the actual [poverty] of the class.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->For a forum dedicated to whining about the mage class, please see: <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://rthen2001.proboards4.com/index.cgi">Rthen's Mage Board</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.<br>
<br>
I have soloed as needed every level from first to well beyond sixtieth.  Fact is a level 50 mage can solo for experience naked except for a stack of malachite.  Mages are the least dependent on dropped items of any class in the game.  Magicians are the least mana bound of any caster as well, limited only by malachite.  Mage AA skills, while they may not look good on paper, have a functional synergy that amplifies their apparent power, and AA can be had by anyone willing to put in the hours.  I can loot my corpse, be fully selfed buffed, and at full mana before rez effects are gone, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> (with only one FT1 item)</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  This all in what I suppose is a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Tier 2</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> guild.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Rthen:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The difference between a modestly equipped Warrior and an uber warrior is far less then a modestly equipped Mage and an uber mage.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This is patently absurd.  Melee classes are far more dependent on gear than casters ever could be, by design.  If I ever get enough inventory space to strip and put my gear in bags, I will happily solo a dark blue at 60 using only a stack of malachite and wearing summoned items.  Equipment matters <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>less</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> to mages than any other class.<br>
<br>
But back to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Noonie</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s original point:<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> raising the level cap is a rare opportunity for verant to patch up everything they view as &quot;wrong&quot;....when verant raises the level cap and adds corresponding content, they are in effect totally redesigning the game and classes, and their relative power to each other as they see fit.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->This is the heart of the matter.  We all know how relative power stood at level 50 pre-<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Kunark</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, magicians were not quite the Lords of Creation, but it was frankly embarassing to be a melee then.  I would med through duels with melees and let <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Gobaner</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> do the ass kicking for me.  Then <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Kunark</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> radically alters the balance of power towards melee 50-60, and until quite recently, it only got worse.  The pendulem has swung greatly in our direction of late: focus items, AA, pet improvements.  It is a matter of debate whether this has gone far enough, but when the pendulem swings one way, guess what happens next?<br>
<br>
I have often disagreed with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Noonie</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, but this time I think she has hit the nail on the head.  <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>If</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> thinks they might have over-done it recently with mages, <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>then</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> the pendulem will swing back towards other classes, most likely melee and possibly priests.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> does verant think mages are overpowered?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Aye, there's the rub.<br>
<br>
